node.text:
Though smack dab in the middle of Los Angeles’ vibrant East Side, this home feels like a secret hideaway. Steps from a street lined with apartment buildings, modest older homes, and commercial warehouses, the single-level house, with just one window on the front facade, looks inward, becoming more open as you move through it to the surprisingly lush backyard. “We wanted to explore indoor/outdoor living in a different way,” says owner Mark Motonaga of @rioshome, who renovated the 1920s-era home with his partner, artist Guy Clouse. Read the complete feature on Atwater Hideaway, nominated in this year’s Dwell Design Awards, when you visit dwell.com/design-awards
–

The founders of @farouki.farouki, a New Orleans architecture and interior design firm, Caroline and Sabri Farouki are behind some of the city’s most visually striking spaces, from the glittery brasserie Justine in the French Quarter to The Odeon at South Market. In a city synonymous with old-world aesthetics, the modern, minimalist home they designed on an empty lot—space that’s hard to come by in a historic neighborhood—is easy to pick out. The front does not feature classic hurricane shutters but sleek, black-framed windows. The petite balcony was a concession to local regulations that the couple now agree gives the house a more copacetic, European appeal in the neighborhood. Inside, the home’s layout is flipped, with the bedrooms for the couple and their two sons downstairs and the living areas and kitchen above to maximize open space and natural light. From a roof deck, the family can take in the neighborhood’s history. "The view was a big surprise for us—and the best surprise," Sabri says. "We never got to see that aspect of the lot when we bought it. The house celebrates New Orleans out of every window." From our July/August issue, see the Farouki’s minimalist home when you pick up a copy of the magazine, or head to the link in our bio.

Modest on the outside and luxurious but understated on the inside, two worlds meet at Villa West: a former gymnasium in the center of Rotterdam that was transformed into a private home by @hiroki_matsuura_ and René Sangers of @masaarchitects. The 1940s sporting hall, originally constructed during World War II, was slated for demolition until the client laid eyes on the building and saw its potential to become a home. After a major renovation that lasted two years, the client and his family now have a serene urban hideout filled with natural light, greenery, and open spaces that flow effortlessly into one another. Perhaps most striking is the home’s bold blend of materials: gritty, exposed brick and concrete, silky stone kitchen countertops, rice-patterned aluminum cabinets, and a glass dining table that changes color over its length from black to brown. See how a gymnasium became an elegant home in Rotterdam when you try Dwell+ at the link in bio.

In Malinalco, Mexico, Casa Mague draws inspiration from the region’s Aztec heritage. “Piramide de Malinalco, one of only three carved pyramids in the world, is part of the town’s daily life,” explains Mauricio Ceballos Pressler, the director and founder of @mcxa.group. “The inhabitants feel proud of their Aztec roots.” To honor them, and in direct reference to the nearby pyramid, an exterior living area adjacent to the pool in the first slide features a curved and stepped wood wall. To more broadly echo a Mesoamerican worldview, Pressler designed each room of the 2,906-square-foot home to feel as if it’s woven into the landscape. “Trees have ritual meaning,” he explains. “The roots symbolize the connection to the underworld, the trunks symbolize the earthly human life, and the branches symbolize the connection with the Gods.” For more on how Casa Mague taps into its cultural roots, head to the link in bio.

After a multi-year search for the perfect midcentury gem to remodel, Los Angeles–based designers Whitney Brown and Carlos Naude stumbled across a neglected 1960s ranch-style home in Woodland Hills and immediately put in an offer. “The house was a diamond in the rough,” says Carlos. “It had great bones—it just needed to be brought back to life.”
Fortunately, the young couple, who are founders of the design firm @workingholidaystudio, were up to the challenge.
The couple sought to “create a place that felt very serene and calming,” says Whitney, explaining why they named their home the Zen Den. “We’ve always been inspired by the sleek minimalism of Scandinavian and Japanese designs,” she adds, noting they also integrated Mexican influences into the space as a way to celebrate Carlos’s heritage. Carlos says, “Overall, we wanted the house to be soothing and easy on the eye.”
A key ingredient the couple relied on for achieving maximum zen was natural light. “From the start, we knew that by installing new doors and windows, the entire aesthetic of the home would change—and that’s exactly what happened,” says Whitney. After researching various companies, the couple decided that @western_window_systems was the perfect fit. “We wanted windows and doors that looked streamlined and modern, but also met all standards of sustainability,” explains Carlos. Throughout the residence, the couple added skylights, picture windows, and sliding doors to draw in light while framing views of the surrounding canyons. “Outdoor living was a big reason we purchased this house,” says Whitney. “Installing the swing-out doors in the dining room was a game changer.”
“Now that the renovation is complete, we don’t want to leave home,” says Whitney. “Being a bit outside of the city, it feels like a vacation. To be able to lay in the grass in peace and quiet while having your child and dog play and run around—it’s truly a gift.” Tour the Japandi-inspired Zen Den at the link in bio.

At the foot of the Western Carpathians in the Czech Republic sits an inviting, two-story holiday home that dates back to the 1800s. Now known as Mezi Lukami (@mezilukami)—Czech for “between meadows”—the historic barn was restored by designer Daniela Hradilová and her partner, Petr Hradil, to serve as the fifth guesthouse for their nearby boutique hotel, Mezi Plutky, which the duo opened in 2017. To make the 19th-century structure rent ready, Hradilováfd brought in experienced local carpenters and stonemasons, using “ingredients” found on-site like stone and wood to reconstruct the volume into an inviting space. Timber walls and beamed ceilings pay homage to the structure’s past, while also complementing the restored, stone-clad walls and floors; sliding glass doors and large picture windows imbue the moody interiors with a natural glow. According to Hradilová, the area’s highly skilled tradespeople made it all possible. “At a time when traditional craftsmanship is disappearing,” she says, “their art and passion is a kind of miracle.” See more of the revamped addition to @meziplutky—or book your stay—at the link in bio.

Some east coasters vacation in Maine, or head west to Palm Springs, but Connecticut couple Hannah and Jamie Lissette were drawn to an entirely different hemisphere. After coming back from a trip to Uruguay, they were so smitten that they soon returned to transform an old ranch house on 59 acres into this off-grid retreat. “Hannah and Jamie imagined Smokewood Garzón as a residence capable of condensing the local country imagery, which is reminiscent of rural life in Montana, where Hannah spent her childhood,” says Andrés Gobba, director and cofounder of @mapaarq. Along with creating self-sufficient systems for energy and water, and adding two new wings to the original structure, MAPA performed a renovation that embraces the original home’s simple silhouette and sloping roofline to honor the region. “The most important original space that has been maintained is the covered gallery, which opens onto the landscape,” says Gobba. “Its simplicity and material austerity seemed to us an important value to preserve and highlight.” See the full feature of the off-grid Uruguayan retreat when you try Dwell+ at the link in bio.

As far as garages go, this one was pretty standard. At the base of a 1930s building in Amsterdam, the car park—formerly a hardware store—came with oil-stained concrete floors, fluorescent lighting, and reflective tape discouraging drivers from scraping the hefty pillars. Not exactly the makings of a warm and inviting family home, but Bart van Seggelen and Valérie Boerma, interior architects and founders of the design firm @bardevanvoltt, thought differently. What the couple saw were 1,075 square feet of open space and the opportunity for single-floor living: a rarity in Amsterdam. “Most apartments of 100-plus square meters are narrow and have multiple floors,” says Valérie. In order to transform the garage into a composed family home—the couple live there with their two children, ages one and five—they took every opportunity to bring in natural light, starting right at the front door. Albert Mo was thrilled to get a call about designing a beach house. “All I could picture in my head on the phone was this amazing cliff top location with ocean views,” says the architect and cofounder of Australian firm @architectseat. “Then, I Googled the address in Flinders, and reality hit,” he says. “The site was inland on a corner block, and bounded by a path locals use to get to the beach.” Not one to be discouraged, Mo got to work designing a home that would maintain privacy from the street while simultaneously providing the family with a beachy retreat. The result is Bellows House, a long, low-slung home built top to bottom with concrete masonry blocks that features a series of open-air moments. The south end of the residence is U-shaped, encircling a courtyard that’s protected from the street by a low wall, also in concrete block. Adjacent to the garage are two private outdoor showers to rinse down surfboards and beach gear. The home’s living spaces open to the north-facing courtyard, a garden where the family gathers and entertains. “I love the casualness and looseness hinted by the wetsuit racks, the outdoor showers, the firepit, and the dining area, which can be completely opened up to the cozy barbecue deck,” says Mo. Tour the breezy Bellows House—known locally as The Pyramids of Flinders—at the link in bio.
